<DOC><DOCNO> AP880324-0325 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 2204EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-PhoneCosts     03-24 0184</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Phone Costs,0192</SECOND><HEAD>McGraw-Hill Says Phone Costs Steady In First Quarter</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Business phone costs held steady in the firstthree months of 1987, the first quarter since 1984 in which theyhave have not fallen, according to a report Thursday.   A 10 percent rise in rates for interstate private lines offsetdeclines of 7 percent in rates for both WATS and toll calls, saidCCMI-McGraw-Hill, which conducts the quarterly survey.   The firm's Telecommunications Price Index remained level at77.3, down from a base of 100 in 1984.   The big three long-distance companies seem to be adjusting theirrates to make it attractive for business customers to switch fromprivate lines to WATS and toll service, said George Christie, chiefeconomist for McGraw-Hill Information Systems Co.   American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co. dominates the interstatelong-distance market, with MCI Communications Corp. and US SprintCommunications Co. trailing.   The cost of local business calling remained stable during theperiod.   Christie said any changes in phone rates in the final days ofthe month would have an insignificant effect on the first-quarterindex.</TEXT></DOC>